arch:property.oc:show_val: Main construction of the Bath Complex.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

Locus 57 consists of the sandstone slab walls of the pool, affixed with copper ties, and the lip resting on these slabs. Sever slabs in 4 rows are exposed of the north section of this locus, and three slabs in three rows are exposed of the south section. The largest slab is in the south section, and is 82 cm in width and 148 cm in height. The slabs are affixed with copper ties, just like those used in the smaller pool of Trench 105/106. The ledges that rest on the slabs are consistent in style. Locus 57 is phased to Stage 2, the main construction of the Bath Complex.
North section: 0.15 m north south -by- 1.60 m east west (exposed); South section: 0.11 m north south -by- 2.78 m east west (exposed).
North section: 1.45 m; South section: 1.48 m.
